"subtopic": "3. Structure And Functions Of Xylem And Phloem",
"content": "Xylem and phloem are the complex, vascular tissues in plant body. While xylem conducts water and minerals, phloem conducts food materials. Let us discuss about these tissues in detail\n\nXylem is a complex tissue, as it consists of both parenchymatous (living thin wall cells) and sclerenchymatous (dead thick walled) cells\n\n• Xylem is composed of four elements as follows :\n\n(i) A tracheid is a non-living, elongated cell with tapering ends. The wall is highly thickened with lignin, except at certain circular spots known as pits\n\n(ii) A vessel is a cylindrical tube-like structure placed one above the other, end to end. The end walls of vessels dissolve partially or completely, forming a continuous channel. A vessel is also a non-living cell with lignified walls\n\nTracheids and vessels are the main conducting elements in the xylem. They both also provide mechanical support to plants\n\n(iii) Xylem parenchyma consists of thick walled living cells. It performs the function of storage\n\n(iv) Xylem fibres are non-living, thick-walled cells which provide mechanical support to plants",
"explanation": "Key points:\n• Xylem is a complex tissue consisting of both parenchymatous and sclerenchymatous cells.\n• Xylem is composed of tracheids, vessels, xylem parenchyma and xylem fibres.\n• A tracheid is a non-living elongated cell with tapering ends.\n• Tracheid walls are highly thickened with lignin except at circular spots called pits.\n• A vessel is a cylindrical tube-like structure placed end to end forming a continuous channel.\n• End walls of vessels dissolve partially or completely to form a continuous channel.\n• Vessels are non-living cells with lignified walls.\n• Tracheids and vessels are the main conducting elements in xylem.\n• Tracheids and vessels provide mechanical support to plants.\n• Xylem parenchyma consists of thick walled living cells performing storage function.\n• Xylem fibres are non-living thick-walled cells providing mechanical support.\n• Xylem and phloem usually occur together in roots, stems and leaves forming vascular bundles.\n• Xylem parenchyma helps in storage of starch and other materials.\n• Tracheids and xylem fibres provide mechanical support to plants.\n• Phloem is a complex tissue consisting of both parenchymatous and sclerenchymatous cells.\n• Phloem consists of sieve tubes, companion cells, phloem parenchyma and phloem fibres.\n• Phloem consists of both living and non-living cells.\n• Sieve tubes are the main conducting elements in phloem.\n• Sieve tubes are elongated cylindrical thin walled cells arranged in vertical rows.\n• Sieve tube end walls are perforated and termed sieve plates.\n\nDefinitions:\n• Xylem and phloem — complex vascular tissues in the plant body\n• Xylem — a complex tissue consisting of both parenchymatous and sclerenchymatous cells\n• A tracheid — a non-living elongated cell with tapering ends\n• Tracheid walls — highly thickened with lignin except at circular spots called pits\n• A vessel — a cylindrical tube-like structure placed end to end forming a continuous channel\n• Vessels — non-living cells with lignified walls\n• Tracheids and vessels — the main conducting elements in xylem\n• Xylem fibres — non-living thick-walled cells providing mechanical support"
