"content": "A membrane that allows certain substances to pass through it, but not others is called a partially permeable membrane or semipermeable membrane. It is a thin membrane, having small pores\n\nGenerally such membranes allow passage (diffusion) of solvent molecules but do not allow the passage of solute molecules through them. For example, plasma membrane is a semipermeable membrane. Egg membrane and cellophane paper are also semipermeable membranes\n\nWater moves into plant cells by osmosis in following manner :\n\nThe cell membrane of the plant cell is a partially permeable membrane\n\nThe cell sap inside the vacuole is a strong solution which contains high concentration of solutes\n\nWater passes into the root hair cell by osmosis because soil contains high concentration of water as compared to root hairs\n\nThe concentration of the sap in the vacuole becomes low due to the high concentration of water\n\nHence, water passes from one cell to another",
