"subtopic": "13. Active Transport",
"content": "The movement of molecules across a semipermeable membrane against a concentration gradient using energy is called active transport . The minerals are absorbed by the root hairs from soil through active transport. The root hair cells contain high concentration of minerals as compared to that in soil. Hence, the movement of minerals from soil to root hair cells requires energy\n\nOn the other hand, passive absorption of water from the soil also takes place, which is controlled by transpiration. The force is created by the transpiration pull and the roots simply act as a passive absorbing surface. In passive transport, energy is not involved\n\nPlants obtain minerals from three sources — atmosphere, water, and soil. Minerals absorbed by plants are returned to the soil by the death and decay of plants and animals\n\nThough a large number of elements are present in the plant body, only some are important for the healthy growth of plants. These are called essential elements\n\nIn all, 16 elements are found to be essential. Depending upon the quantity of these elements required by the plants, the elements are grouped into two categories:\n\n(i) Macronutrients, which are required in large quantities. Examples of Macronutrients: Carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, sulphur, calcium and magnesium\n\n(ii) Micronutrients, which are required in trace amounts. These are also called trace elements\n\nExamples of Micronutrients : Chlorine, iron, copper, boron,",
