"type": "note",
"subtopic": "21. Honeybees — Apiculture",
"content": "The insects which provide us honey are known as honeybees. The honeybees keep honey in their nest, which is known as the beehive. A beehive has small compartments — combs. The shape and size of the comb depends on the type of bees\n\nThe place or artificial beehive used for the rearing of honeybees is called an \"apiary\"\n\nAll activities such as laying of eggs, rearing of the larvae and pupae are done in the combs\n\nThree types of adults are present in the beehive — queen, drone (male) and workers\n\nThere is only one queen in the whole of the colony. Its function is to lay eggs\n\nDrones are smaller in size than the queen and their function is to fertilise the queen\n\nWorkers are the undeveloped females. They cannot lay eggs. Their function is to look after the queen and also keep the colony clean\n\nHoneybees are mainly used to extract honey and beeswax. Honey is a rich source of carbohydrates. Beeswax is used in making candles, cosmetics, etc. Honey is produced by honeybees from the nectar of flowers. It consists of water, sugar, minerals and enzymes. It is an antiseptic and easily digestible. For this reason, honey is used in medicines",
